post.author: bpanjavan
post.title: Accessing SQL Server 2008 Remotely
post.content:
I recently had a little trouble setting up SQL Server 2008 in my home infrastructure.  I've posted the instructions to setting up access for SQL Server 2008 Remotely so that you (and more importantly ME) don't have to go struggle through it again.

  • Enable Remote Access in SQL Server Management Studio
    • From Management Studio, Right-click on the instance you want to enable and select Properties


    • Check the box labeled Allow remote connections to this server.  Click OK.


  • Create an Inbound Rule in Windows Firewall to open a TCP Port
    • From the Start menu, open Windows Firewall with Advanced Security

    • From the Left Navigation, Right-click Inbound Rules and click New Rule…

      Select       Port.  Click Next
    • In the top section, select TCP.  In the bottom section, select Specific local ports and enter 1433 in the textbox (SQL uses port 1433 by default.  There's a chance your instance is configured differently but that won't matter in the next step).  Click Next
    • Select Allow the connection.  Click Next.
    • This step specifies when to open the port.  Check the options you're comfortable with.  I only checked the top 2 (Domain and Private) because personally I'm not comfortable exposing ANY ports to the public.  Click Next
    • Specify a Name and Description at your choosing.  Click Finish
    • You should see the new rule appear under the list of Inbound Rules


  • Configure SQL Server Network Configuration
    • Open SQL Server Configuration Manager from the Start menu

    • Expand SQL Server Network Configuration and select Protocols for SQL 2008

      • Double-click TCP/IP
    • Under the Protocol Tab, ensure that Enabled is set to Yes
    • Under the IP Addresses tab, scroll all the way to the bottom and enter 1433 under TCP Port

      • Click OK.  The configuration manager will notify you that changes won't take effect until you restart the SQL Service

  • Restart the SQL Service
    • From the left navigation of SQL Server Configuration Manager, select SQL Server Services
    • Right-click SQL Server (SQL 2008) and select Restart


 

 

Note that the above instructions work just as well for SQL Express.

comment.author: Stephen Kalsow
comment.content: Zune and iPod: Most people compare the Zune to the Touch, but after seeing how slim and surprisingly small and light it is, I consider it to be a rather unique hybrid that combines qualities of both the Touch and the Nano. comment.author: Gerald Labs
comment.content: This is getting a bit more subjective, but I much prefer the Zune Marketplace. The interface is colorful, has more flair, and some cool features like 'Mixview' that let you quickly see related albums, songs, or other users related to what you're listening to. Clicking on one of those will center on that item, and another set of "neighbors" will come into view, allowing you to navigate around exploring by similar artists, songs, or users. Speaking of users, the Zune "Social" is also great fun, letting you find others with shared tastes and becoming friends with them. You then can listen to a playlist created based on an amalgamation of what all your friends are listening to, which is also enjoyable. Those concerned with privacy will be relieved to know you can prevent the public from seeing your personal listening habits if you so choose.
